statement:
Consider the matrix

\begin{align*}
A=\begin{bmatrix}
3  &  2\\
2  &  3
\end{bmatrix}.
\end{align*}

For each eigenvalue of A, find an eigenvector.

sols:
Refer to the previous part for the eigenvalue computations. For the
eigenvalue $\displaystyle \lambda = 1$

\begin{align*}
A-I=\begin{bmatrix}
2  &  2\\
2  &  2
\end{bmatrix}.
\end{align*}

and from this we see that the vector
$\begin{bmatrix} 1 \\ -1 \end{bmatrix}$ is an eigenvector. For the
$\displaystyle \lambda = 5$ eigenvalue,

\begin{align*}
A-5I=\begin{bmatrix}
-2  &  2\\
2  &  -2
\end{bmatrix}.
\end{align*}

and from this we see that the vector
$\begin{bmatrix} 1 \\ 1 \end{bmatrix}$ is an eigenvector.
